File: The Standing Committee on Public Accounts (Scopa) says SAA's failure to submit two sets of financial statements and annual reports to Parliament, is of grave concern. JOHANNESBURG - The Standing Committee on Public Accounts (Scopa) says SAA's failure to submit two sets of financial statements and annual reports to Parliament, is of grave concern. Scopa says reasons given by the airline are not satisfactory. WATCH: SAA faces Scopa SAA was set to submit legal opinion and other documents by the 20th of November, which they failed to do. Scopa needs the documents to prepare for its meeting with the Auditor General, the Department of Public Enterprises and National Treasury on Wednesday. The Committee has made it clear, it will continue with its planned meeting with or without the airline's cooperation.